# FRDs — Functional Requirements Documents

This folder is where **incremental instructions mature into agreed specs** before they become plans.
It exists for **large, multi-module initiatives** — where requirements should be consolidated and
agreed *per module* before any code. (Small Tier-1 changes skip this entirely — changelog + build.)

> **When to use FRDs:** the default workflow is lightweight (describe-it-in-chat → build). Reach for
> FRDs when the owner is introducing a big new surface area (a new product area, a major subsystem, a
> CRM/billing/portal expansion) that is really *many* features. Each module gets one FRD: a captured,
> agreed statement of *what that module must do*, so it is never lost and a fresh session can pick it up.

---

## Where an FRD sits in the workflow

```
 INSTRUCTIONS (owner, in chat — any form: bullets, paragraphs, a doc, screenshots)
      │  logged dated →
      ▼
 ../<NN>-requirements-changelog.md      raw capture, never lost
      │  consolidated by module →
      ▼
 frds/FRD-NN-<module>.md                the agreed spec  ← YOU ARE HERE
      │  status: Draft → In Review → Approved
      │  owner approves →
      ▼
 ../../plans/upcoming/NN-<module>/plan.md   technical approach + acceptance
      │  "build it" →
      ▼
 ../../plans/inprogress/  (+tasks.md)  →  ../../plans/done/
      │  on ship →
      ▼
 ../<module>.md  (durable "how it works")   + ../../database/database.md
```

The FRD bridges **raw instructions** and a **plan**. The changelog says *"the owner asked for X on
date Y."* The FRD says *"here is the full, agreed definition of module X."* The plan says *"here is
how we'll build it."*

## Lifecycle — status is a field in the FRD header (the file does NOT move)

| Status | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| **Draft** | Being filled from incoming instructions. Open questions outstanding. Expect churn. |
| **In Review** | Requirements captured; owner + assistant resolving the open-questions list. |
| **Approved** | Owner has signed off. Frozen enough to plan against. |
| **Promoted** | A plan now exists. The FRD is the requirements-of-record; later changes get a dated entry in its Change Log, never a silent rewrite. |

Unlike plans (whose folder = status), an FRD stays in `frds/` permanently as the requirements record.

## How to create / update an FRD

- Copy [`_TEMPLATE.md`](_TEMPLATE.md) → `FRD-NN-<short-module-name>.md` (next free number; reserve
  `FRD-00` for the initiative's vision / module map if there is one).
- Fill what's known; everything unresolved goes in **Open Questions** — that list drives the discussion.
- When a new instruction arrives for an existing module, log it to the changelog **and** fold it into
  that module's FRD (add a dated line to the FRD's **Change Log** if it changes agreed scope).
- Keep it factual and concise. No secrets, no real PII (use synthetic examples).

